I didn't say it was simple, I said it was a case of applying a suitable
amount of cash. I disagree about wind power - the problem of wind power
for general use is that it's inconsistent, but if your intention is to
generate hydrogen as and when it's windy and store it, in a larger
quantity than you can fit in the car, and you have the tech to do so,
then that's not a problem; in fact, it makes it an ideal problem for a
wind generator. As far as solar is concerned, the efficiency is limited
by the technology, not by thermodynamic limitations, so it is a question
of requiring more research. The main problem with local generation of
power and fuel is that no serious player in the market wants to support
it, for obvious reasons.

