That's a very jaded view of peer review. My experience of peer review
has been that people are only quick to point out where there are
mistakes or conclusions that are not adequately supported by the
evidence presented in the paper - which usually means going back to the
literature to find additional supporting work done by someone else.
Obviously people have their own hobby horses, and the comments you
receive often reflect the interests and previous work of the reviewer.
But I've never known a reviewer to go beyond that and say that the
results I have generated are wrong because they don't show the same
things as their work - the truth is really that if you are going to
contradict an already peer reviewed and widely accepted theory, then you
have to have very good evidence that says you're right. That is the
purpose of peer review, otherwise, what you get is wikipedia, where
anyone can write whatever they like.

I remember a conspiracy theory program on TV that investigated the
furore surrounding the researchers who claimed to have developed cold
fusion. No one would accept their results, no one managed to repeat
their results, no one wanted to publish them or fund them. At the end of
the program, they had managed to get some poor idiots to pay them to try
to make a bigger "cold fusion reactor", and, well, the lack of any news
on that front is surely a point in favour of peer review. And in the
case of climate change, there should be companies just lining up to pay
money to any credible scientist who will stand up and say that we're not
contributing to global warming at all.

